The ELOs, together, with the Europool offciers, analysts and other experts, provide and effective and quick service 24 hours a day
The Europol staff,  including the ELOs and security personnel, will reach 485 by the end of 2004.
Management and control stop at national borders and has been active in establishing cooperative networks
In addition, Europol improved its international law-enforcement cooperation by negotiating bilateral operational or strategic agreements with other States and international organisations: Colombia, Eurojust, European Central Bank, European Monitoring Centre on Drugs and Drug Addiction, Iceland, Interpol, Norway, Romania, Russia, United States of America and World Customs Organisation.
Fact sheet on Europol
January 2004 â€” EN
Europol reports to the Council of Ministers for Justice and Home Affairs.
The Council oversees the guidance and control of Europol.
JHA appoints the Director/Deputy Directors and approves the budget.
The Council of Ministers have representatives from Member States, requirements for uimous decisions helps ensure a democratic control of Europol.
The Europol Management Board has one representative from each Member State and supervises the activities of the organization.
Europol, the European Union law-enforcement organisation,  handles criminal intelligence.
Its aim is to improve the effectiveness and cooperation between the competent authorities of the Member States in combating serious international organized crime.
Its mission includes significant contributions to the EU's law-enforcement action against organized crime, emphasizing criminal organizations.
Two data protection experts from each Member State comprise the Joint Supervisory Body which monitors the content/use of personal data in Europol.
